<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="124">
<bibRefCitation author="Bearez, P" journalOrPublisher="Cybium" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" pagination="61 - 62" refId="B1" refString="Bearez, P, 2003. Premier signalement de Scolopsistaeniopterus (Nemipteridae) et de Gymnocraniuselongatus (Lethrinidae) en Nouvelle-Caledonie. . Cybium 27: 61 - 62" title="Premier signalement de Scolopsistaeniopterus (Nemipteridae) et de Gymnocraniuselongatus (Lethrinidae) en Nouvelle-Caledonie." volume="27" year="2003">
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="124" start="start">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Béarez">Bearez</normalizedToken>
</pageBreakToken>
(2003)
</bibRefCitation>
reported three specimens [MNHN 2002-2930 (designated here as the holotype of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. lacrima" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">S. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Holotype of Scolopsis lacrima sp. nov., MNHN 2002 - 2930, 213.6 mm SL, Grande-Terre Island, New Caledonia a fresh condition (photo by P. Bearez) b preserved condition." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.861.35052.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/315276" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), MNHN-ICOS-00437, and DASMN-52] as 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemipteridae" genus="Scolopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scolopsis taeniopterus" order="Perciformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="taeniopterus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Scolopsis taeniopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Cuvier, 1830) from New Caledonia. The latter two specimens have been reduced to bones and otoliths only. However, fresh colour photographs of both specimens prior to dissection (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Colour photographs of Scolopsis lacrima sp. nov., Grande-Terre Island, New Caledonia (photos by P. Bearez) a DASMN- 52, 187 mm SL b MNHN-ICOS- 00437, 192 mm SL." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.861.35052.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/315281" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) support their identification here as 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. lacrima" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">S. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="124">
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemipteridae" genus="Scolopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scolopsis meridiana" order="Perciformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meridiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Scolopsis meridiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. taenioptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" rank="species" species="taenioptera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">S. taenioptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are restricted to northern Australia and Southeast Asia, respectively (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution records of Scolopsis lacrima sp. nov. (star), S. meridiana (circles), and S. taenioptera (triangles), based on specimens examined in Nakamura et al. (2018) and this study." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.861.35052.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/315277" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), probably not occurring in New Caledonia, suggesting that the three species of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Nemipteridae" genus="Scolopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scolopsis" order="Perciformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Scolopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a reddish blotch on the upper part of the pectoral-fin base are allopatrically distributed in the Indo-West Pacific.
</paragraph>
